Removing all the null values might result in loosing most of the important data points, Thus we will replace the null values with appropriate values.First lets choose the column of interest only.

Attaching package: dplyr

The following objects are masked from package:base:

crime_data1_cleaned <- crime_data_1 %>%
  select(
    Record_Number = `DR_NO`, 
    Reported_Crime_Date = `Date Rptd`,
    Actual_Crime_Date = `DATE OCC`,
    Actual_Crime_Time = `TIME OCC`,
    Area = `AREA`,
    Area_Name = `AREA NAME`,
    Reported_District_Number = `Rpt Dist No`,
    Crime_Code = `Crm Cd`,
    Crime_Code_Desc = `Crm Cd Desc`,
    Victim_Age = `Vict Age`,
    Victim_Sex = `Vict Sex`,
    Victim_Cultural_Group = `Vict Descent`,
    Premis_Code = `Premis Cd`,
    Premis_Desc = `Premis Desc`,
    Weapon_Used_Code = `Weapon Used Cd`,
    Weapon_Desc = `Weapon Desc`,
    File_Status = `Status`,
    File_Status_Desc = `Status Desc`,
    Crime_Code_1 = `Crm Cd 1`,
    Crime_Location = `LOCATION`,
    Location_Cross_Street = `Cross Street`,
    Latitude = `LAT`,
    Longitude = `LON`
  )%>%
  mutate(
    Record_Number = as.numeric(Record_Number),
    Reported_Crime_Date = as.Date(Reported_Crime_Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p"),
    Actual_Crime_Date = as.Date(Actual_Crime_Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p"),
   Actual_Crime_Time = sprintf("%04d", as.integer(Actual_Crime_Time)),
    Actual_Crime_Time = paste(substr(Actual_Crime_Time, 1, 2), substr(Actual_Crime_Time, 3, 4), sep = ":"),
    Actual_Crime_Time = hm(Actual_Crime_Time),
    Reported_District_Number = as.integer(Reported_District_Number),
    Crime_Code = as.integer(Crime_Code),
    Victim_Age = as.numeric(Victim_Age),
    Premis_Code = as.numeric(Premis_Code),
    Weapon_Used_Code = as.numeric(Weapon_Used_Code),
    Crime_Code_1 = as.numeric(Crime_Code_1),
    Area = as.factor(Area),
    Latitude = as.numeric(Latitude),
    Longitude = as.numeric(Longitude)
  )

Checking the null values now

crime_data1_filtered <- crime_data1_cleaned %>%
  filter(
    Victim_Age != 0, !is.na(Victim_Age),
    Victim_Sex != "unknown", !is.na(Victim_Sex),
    Victim_Cultural_Group != "unknown", !is.na(Victim_Cultural_Group),
    Premis_Code != 0, !is.na(Premis_Code),
    Premis_Desc != 0, !is.na(Premis_Desc),
    Weapon_Used_Code != 0, !is.na(Weapon_Used_Code),
    Weapon_Desc != 0, !is.na(Weapon_Desc),
    File_Status != 0, !is.na(File_Status),
    Crime_Code_1 != 0, !is.na(Crime_Code_1),
    Location_Cross_Street != 0, !is.na(Location_Cross_Street),
    !is.na(Weapon_Used_Code)
  )

crime_data2_filtered <- crime_data2_cleaned %>%

Checking if any duplicate record exists

duplicate_counts1 <- concatenated_df %>%
  group_by(across(everything())) %>% 
  summarise(Count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  filter(Count > 1)

Exploratory data analysis

Crime trend analysis ove time

library(ggplot2)
library(lubridate)

crime_data_by_year <- concatenated_df %>%
  mutate(Year = year(Reported_Crime_Date)) %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarise(Num_Crimes = n(), .groups = 'drop')


ggplot(crime_data_by_year, aes(x = reorder(Year, Num_Crimes), y = Num_Crimes)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue", color = "black") +  # Bar plot
  scale_x_discrete(name = "Year") +  # Adjusting x scale to be discrete
  labs(title = "Number of Crimes Reported Per Year",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Number of Crimes") +
  theme_minimal()

Geographic Distribution

crime_data_by_area <- concatenated_df %>%
  group_by(Area_Name) %>%
  summarise(Num_Crimes = n(), .groups = 'drop') 

ggplot(crime_data_by_area, aes(x = reorder(Area_Name, -Num_Crimes), y = Num_Crimes, fill = Area_Name)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) + 
  labs(title = "Geographic Distribution of Crimes by Area",
       x = "Area",
       y = "Number of Crimes") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Victim Demographics

A - Other Asian B - Black C - Chinese D - Cambodian F - Filipino G - Guamanian H - Hispanic/Latin/Mexican I - American Indian/Alaskan Native J - Japanese K - Korean L - Laotian O - Other P - Pacific Islander S - Samoan U - Hawaiian V - Vietnamese W - White X - Unknown Z - Asian Indian


crime_summary <- concatenated_df %>%
   group_by(Victim_Sex,Victim_Cultural_Group) %>%
   summarize(
     Count_Crime_Code_1 = sum(Crime_Code_1 > 0, na.rm = TRUE),
     .groups = "drop"
   )

cultural_group_labels <- c(
  A = "Other Asian", B = "Black", C = "Chinese", D = "Cambodian", 
  F = "Filipino", G = "Guamanian", H = "Hispanic/Latin/Mexican", 
  I = "American Indian/Alaskan Native", J = "Japanese", K = "Korean", 
  L = "Laotian", O = "Other", P = "Pacific Islander", S = "Samoan", 
  U = "Hawaiian", V = "Vietnamese", W = "White",
  Z = "Asian Indian"
)

# Assuming crime_summary$Victim_Cultural_Group contains abbreviations like "A", "B", etc.
crime_summary <- crime_summary %>%
  mutate(Victim_Cultural_Group = factor(Victim_Cultural_Group, levels = names(cultural_group_labels), labels = cultural_group_labels))

# Plotting the data with bars sorted by Count_Crime_Code_1 and custom labels for cultural groups
ggplot(crime_summary, aes(x = reorder(Victim_Cultural_Group, -Count_Crime_Code_1), y = Count_Crime_Code_1, fill = "Crime Code 1")) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  labs(title = "Crime Type Counts by Victim Cultural Group",
       x = "Victim Cultural Group",
       y = "Count of Crimes",
       fill = "Crime Code") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

crime_summary <- concatenated_df %>%
  group_by(Victim_Age) %>%
  summarize(
    Count_Crime_Code_1 = sum(Crime_Code_1 > 0, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) 

ggplot(crime_summary, aes(x = Victim_Age)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = Count_Crime_Code_1, fill = "Crime Code 1"), stat = "identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  labs(title = "Crime Type Counts by Victim Age",
       x = "Victim Age",
       y = "Count of Crimes",
       fill = "Crime Code") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
